---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
---

<Layout>
  <Navigation />

  <main class="review">
    <h1>Elden Ring</h1>

    <div class="info">
      <p><strong>Platform:</strong> PC</p>
      <p><strong>First Playthrough:</strong> 2022 • 120 hrs</p>
      <p><strong>DLC:</strong> 2024 • 35 hrs</p>
      <p><strong>Genre:</strong> Action RPG / Soulslike</p>
      <p>
        <strong>Recommended for:</strong> Players who enjoy exploration and challenging
        combat.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>First Impressions</h2>

    <p>
      I thought I'd start here since it's one of my favourite games of all
      time... A masterpiece of world-building that redefined what open-world
      RPGs could be, even if its size eventually works against it.
    </p>

    <h2>Atmosphere & World</h2>

    <p>
      The atmosphere is what's driving the Souls games and this one nails it.
      You can feel the history woven into the world by George R. R. Martin. You
      can see the hints of his earlier books in the game. As with many of
      Martin's stories, several important character names even share his
      initials. It's a fun little detail, even if it isn't something I
      particularly care about.
    </p>

    <p>
      Going through the Lands Between is scary, but in the good kind. You are
      always learning something new, getting some new equipment or getting
      closure or the next steps to a questline. There's always something more.
      And even when you think that there isn't, the game takes your jaw and
      pulls it to the ground.
    </p>

    <p>
      And that is much to do with the artwork of the game. The game feels like
      you are stepping inside of a painting. Everything is meticulously curated
      to the last sand grain.
    </p>

    <h2>Content & Replayability</h2>

    <p>
      Elden Ring is the most "gamey" of all the Souls games because of the sheer
      amount of side content and repeated content. That, for me, doesn't bring
      the game up or down—it just means there's more game to play.
    </p>

    <p>
      That also makes the game less repeatable than the other Souls games
      because of my completionist personality.
    </p>

    <p>
      I've played through the game a couple of times, including the DLC, but
      even with how much I love the game, I cannot start a new journey. There's
      just so much content that starting a new playthrough is scary and takes a
      lot, a LOT of time.
    </p>

    <p>For a first playthrough, Elden Ring feels like every gamer's dream.</p>

    <h2>Combat</h2>

    <p>
      The amount of content actually hits the player in the end game. You can
      love something all you want, but if you repeat the same pattern every day,
      for several hours, you'll grow tired, get bored, and eventually even end
      up disliking the whole thing.
    </p>

    <p>And I have to say, Elden Ring can feel a bit like that.</p>

    <p>
      The combat mechanics of the game, whilst satisfying, can get samey after
      around 150 hours of gameplay.
    </p>

    <h2>Music & DLC</h2>

    <p>Have to mention the score somewhere.</p>

    <p>
      I think this was one of the weakest parts of the main game, but it is
      completely turned around in the DLC. The DLC gives three of my favourite
      Souls tracks of all time.
    </p>

    <p>
      Also worth noting, I think most of the best stuff in the game comes from
      the DLC. This is not to say that the main game is weak in any way, but
      rather that the DLC is definitely the strongest part.
    </p>

    <p>From the bosses, world design, questlines and the score.</p>

    <p>
      For repeated playthroughs, however, the DLC can be a bit rough. Gathering
      the Scadutree Fragments all over the world is fine on the first go around,
      but can become a bit tedious on the second.
    </p>

    <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

    <p>If you like RPG's as much as I do, this game is a no-brainer.</p>

    <p>
      And even if you don't, I'd still recommend it, as long as you aren't
      completely new to gaming.
    </p>

    <p>
      The game is hard. Belonging to the Souls genre, there's no question about
      it. And I think it's the biggest hurdle for new players.
    </p>

    <p>
      But if you've got the persistence, this game will open your eyes to the
      game industry as a whole.
    </p>

    <p>
      Games don't need to be as hand-holdy as Ubisoft makes them. They become
      more special when you get to figure out the basic mechanics and what to do
      in the world by yourself.
    </p>

    <p>How you want to approach the problems is the slogan of the game.</p>

    <h2>Ratings</h2>

    <div class="ratings">
      <div class="rating">
        <h3>Player's Rating</h3>

        <span>9.5 / 10</span>
      </div>

      <div class="rating">
        <h3>Engineering Perspective</h3>

        <span>6 / 10</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="again">
      <h2>Would I Play It Again?</h2>

      <p>Yes—but not anytime soon.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  .review {
    max-width: 900px;

    margin: 80px auto;

    padding: 0 30px;
  }

  .review h1 {
    font-size: 3rem;

    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }

  .review h2 {
    margin-top: 60px;

    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }

  .review p {
    line-height: 1.8;

    font-size: 1.08rem;
  }

  .info {
    display: inline-block;

    padding: 20px 28px;

    margin: 25px 0 50px;

    border: 1px solid var(--border);

    border-radius: 12px;

    background: var(--card);
  }

  .info p {
    margin: 8px 0;

    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .ratings {
    display: flex;

    gap: 20px;

    margin-top: 30px;
  }

  .rating {
    flex: 1;

    padding: 20px;

    border: 1px solid var(--border);

    border-radius: 12px;

    background: var(--card);

    text-align: center;
  }

  .rating h3 {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .rating span {
    font-size: 1.8rem;

    color: var(--accent);

    font-weight: bold;
  }

  .again {
    margin-top: 40px;

    padding: 18px 24px;

    border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);

    background: var(--card);

    border-radius: 10px;
  }

  .again h2 {
    margin: 0 0 10px;

    font-size: 1.4rem;
  }

  .again p {
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
